</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[113,1090,290,732]" pageId="19" pageNumber="734">
Male (
<typeStatus box="[213,309,420,444]" pageId="19" pageNumber="734">paratype</typeStatus>
, 
<figureCitation box="[321,401,420,444]" captionStart="Figs 52–55" captionStartId="21.[113,150,1511,1530]" captionTargetBox="[170,1033,222,1469]" captionTargetId="figure-14@21.[163,1040,218,1474]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs 52–55. Habitus. 52 – Hesperopenna bonifaci sp. nov. (male, holotype, 9.5 mm); 53 – H. helferi sp. nov. (male, paratype, 8.5 mm); 54 – H. sipekorum sp. nov. (male, holotype, 8.6 mm); 55 – H. zofka sp. nov. (male, holotype, 6.9 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740065/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="734">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
). Body completely brown, apical half of elytra somewhat paler, apices of mandibles black, antennae gradually darkened from antennomere III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[113,1090,290,732]" pageId="19" pageNumber="734">
Interocular space twice as wide as transverse diameter of eye. Antennae 0.75 times as long as body, length ratio of antennomeres I to XI equals 16-5-7-15-15-15-16-15-16-14-17. Pronotum 1.55 times as broad as long. Elytra glabrous, 1.65 times as long as wide (measured at humeral calli), 0.72 times as long as body. Length ratio of metatarsomeres 1–4 equals 12- 7-5-11. Last ventrite posteriorly without two small incisions (
<figureCitation box="[768,848,612,636]" captionStart="Figs 19–26" captionStartId="15.[112,149,1058,1077]" captionTargetBox="[124,1078,218,1029]" captionTargetId="figure-153@15.[113,1088,207,1034]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs 19–26. Last abdominal ventrite of males.19 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom. nov.; 20 – H. persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 21 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 22 – H. arnoldi sp. nov.; 23 – H. bonifaci sp. nov.; 24 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 25 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 26 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740049" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740049/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="734">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[113,1090,290,732]" pageId="19" pageNumber="734">
Aedeagus: dorsal side with long thin incision; apex ventrally with high thin keel in the middle and deep U-shaped incision on right side (
<figureCitation box="[644,724,676,700]" captionStart="Figs 15–18" captionStartId="13.[115,152,1542,1561]" captionTargetBox="[126,1079,226,1362]" captionTargetId="figure-14@13.[113,1090,218,1370]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 15–18. Aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view; c – ventral view). 15 – H. bonifaci sp. nov.; 16 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 17 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 18 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740045/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="734">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[113,1090,290,732]" lastBlockId="23.[113,1089,219,596]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="738" pageId="19" pageNumber="734">
Female. Apex of last ventrite with three very small protrusions (median and two lateral) (
<figureCitation box="[121,201,219,244]" captionStart="Figs 27–33" captionStartId="17.[113,149,1518,1537]" captionTargetBox="[138,1066,210,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-14@17.[135,1067,206,1474]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs 27–33.Last abdominal ventrite of females. 27 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom.nov.; 28 – H.persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 29 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 30 – H. arnoldi sp. nov.; 31 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 32 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 33 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740051/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="738">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
), pygidium with small U-shaped incision at apex (
<figureCitation box="[750,831,219,244]" captionStart="Figs 34–40" captionStartId="18.[151,188,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[231,1053,221,1476]" captionTargetId="figure-10@18.[218,1059,210,1480]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 34–40. Female pygidium. 34 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom. nov.; 35 – H. persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 36 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 37 – H. arnoldi sp. nov.; 38 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 39 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 40 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740055/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="738">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
). Spermatheca: nodulus relatively narrow, subtubular, slightly extended apically, cornu regularly rounded, slightly wider than nodulus, apical appendage quadrangular (
<figureCitation box="[677,757,283,307]" captionStart="Figs 41–47" captionStartId="19.[112,149,1518,1537]" captionTargetBox="[208,996,760,1504]" captionTargetId="figure-215@19.[204,1000,749,1508]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs 41–47. Spermatheca. 41 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom. nov.; 42 – H. persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 43 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 44 – H. arnoldi sp. nov.; 45 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 46 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 47 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740059/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="738">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
